  1. Use rename() to rename the columns and make them easier to use. The new column names should be:
  • country
  • commname
  • ASFIS_sciname
  • ASFIS_spcode
  • ISSCAAP_spgroup
  • ISSCAAP_spgroupname
  • FAO_area
  • unit
fisheries <- rename(fisheries,
    country = Country,
    commname = `Common name`,
    ASFIS_sciname = `ASFIS species name`,
    ASFIS_spcode = `ASFIS species#`,
    ISSCAAP_spgroup = `ISSCAAP group#`,
    ISSCAAP_spgroupname = `ISSCAAP taxonomic group`,
    FAO_area = `FAO major fishing area`,
    unit = Measure)

  1. Are these data tidy? Why or why not, and, how do you know? Use the appropriate pivot function to tidy the data. Remove the NA’s. Put the tidy data frame into a new object fisheries_tidy.
    #No they are not tidy because the year data are column names.
fisheries_tidy <- 
  fisheries %>% 
  pivot_longer("1950":"2012",
               names_to = "year",
               values_to = "tonnes",
               values_drop_na = TRUE)
